Find the vector $\mathbf{v}$ such that
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix}\]and
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix}.\]
inference:
Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$. We have
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{a}} \mathbf{v} = \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2} \mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix}\]and
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{b}} \mathbf{v} = \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|^2} \mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix}.\]From the first equation,
\[\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}}{5} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix},\]so
\[\mathbf{v} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{38}{5} \cdot 5 = 38.\]From the second equation,
\[\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}}{13} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix},\]so
\[\mathbf{v} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{58}{13} \cdot 13 = 58.\]Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}.$ Then $2x + y = 38$ and $2x + 3y = 58.$ Subtracting the first equation from the second gives $2y = 20,$ so $y = 10.$ Then $2x = 38 - 10 = 28,$ so $x = 14.$ Thus $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 14 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}.$

\boxed{$\begin{pmatrix} 14 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}$}
I hope it is correct.
